In the [[:en:Department of Divinities|Department of Divinities]] (Department of Shinto Affairs) of the {{ill|Imperial Court of Japan|ja|朝廷 (日本)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Court of Japan|qq=}}, the {{ill|Four Seasonal Festivals|ja|四時祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Four Seasonal Festivals|qq=}} designated the '''Ainame Festival''' ({{ill|Ainame Festival|ja|相嘗祭|lt=Ainame-sai|Ainame Festival=Ainame Festival|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ainame Festival|qq=}}), '''Chinkon Festival''' ({{ill|Chinkon-sai|ja|鎮魂祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinkon-sai|qq=}}), and '''Niiname Festival''' ([[:en:Niiname-no-Matsuri|Niiname-sai]]) in the '''ddth month of the old calendar''' as '''Winter Festivals'''. Additionally, although the '''Tsukinami Festival''' ({{ill|Tsukinami-sai|ja|月次祭|1=Tsukinami-no-Matsuri|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukinami-sai|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukinami-no-Matsuri|qq=}}), '''Chinka (Fire-Calming Ritual)''' ({{ill|Fire-Pacification Festival|ja|鎮火|Fire-Pacification Festival=Fire-Pacification Festival|lt=Chinka|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fire-Pacification Festival|qq=}}), and '''Dōkyō Festival''' ({{ill|Dōkyō|ja|道饗|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dōkyō|qq=}}) were not inherently winter-specific, they were conducted as part of the Winter Festival period.
Today, many '''Winter Festivals''' retain elements of the '''Chinkon Festival (Ritual for Soul-Pacification)''', and practices such as '''Yutate (Hot Water Purification Rituals)''' ({{ill|Yutate|ja|湯立|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yutate|qq=}}) and '''Kagura (Sacred Dance and Music)''' ([[:en:Kagura|Kagura]]), which originated from '''Shimotsuki Kagura''' ({{ill|Shimotsuki Kagura|ja|霜月神楽|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimotsuki Kagura|qq=}}), are often performed.
